'''George Ryan Bingham'''  (born March 31, 1981) is an American singer, songwriter, and guitarist whose music spans multiple genres.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Gold |first1=Scott |title=Raw and Genuine |url=https://www.latimes.com/archives/la-xpm-2008-mar-30-ca-bingham30-story.html |newspaper=LA Times |date=March 30, 2008 |access-date=June 27, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Hajek |first1=Daniel |title=From Rodeo To Radio: Ryan Bingham's Wild Ride |url=https://www.npr.org/2013/12/29/256347468/from-rodeo-to-radio-ryan-binghams-wild-ride |newspaper=NPR.org |publisher=NPR |access-date=June 27, 2019}}</ref> He is currently based in Los Angeles.<ref>{{cite web|first=Tom |last=LanHam |title=Ryan Bingham is happier out of Hollywood spotlight |url=https://www.sfexaminer.com/entertainment/ryan-bingham-is-happier-out-of-hollywood-spotlight/ |work=SFExaminer |date=March 2019 |access-date=June 21, 2019}}</ref> As of 2019, Bingham has released six studio albums and one live album, the last four of which were released under his own label, Axster Bingham Records.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Isaac |first1=Nico |title=Ryan Bingham: Tomorrowland |date=September 17, 2012 |url=https://www.pastemagazine.com/articles/2012/09/ryan-bingham-tomorrowland.html |publisher=Paste Magazine |access-date=June 27, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Horowitz |first1=Hal |title=Ryan Bingham: Fear and Saturday Night |url=https://americansongwriter.com/2015/01/ryan-bingham-fear-saturday-night/ |website=American Songwriter |date=January 20, 2015 |access-date=June 27, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Skinner |first1=Jared |title=Ryan Bingham: Ryan Bingham Live |url=https://www.popmatters.com/ryan-bingham-ryan-bingham-live-2495408357.html |website=PopMatters.com|date=November 28, 2016 |access-date=June 27, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Beaugez |first1=Jim |title=How Ryan Bingham's Album 'American Love Song' Addresses Border Politics |url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-country/ryan-bingham-new-album-american-love-song-793600/ |website=RollingStone Magazine |access-date=June 27, 2019 |date=February 12, 2019}}</ref>

Originally from [[Hobbs, New Mexico]], Bingham grew up across the Southwestern United States. He joined the rodeo circuit as a bull rider in his teens.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Schlanger |first1=Talia |title=Ryan Bingham's Rugged And Raw 'American Love Song' |url=https://www.npr.org/sections/world-cafe/2019/06/03/729258867/ryan-binghams-rugged-and-raw-american-love-song |newspaper=NPR.org |publisher=NPR |access-date=June 27, 2019 |date=June 3, 2019}}</ref> Bingham learned music on a guitar gifted to him by his mother at age 16, initially playing after [[rodeo]]s for his friends.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Essmaker |first1=Tina |title=Ryan Bingham MUSICIAN SONGWRITER |url=http://thegreatdiscontent.com/interview/ryan-bingham |website=The Great Discontent |access-date=June 27, 2019 |date=January 15, 2013}}</ref> Eventually, he began playing in small bars and honky tonks across the West, landing him in Los Angeles. Bingham signed his first record deal with [[Lost Highway Records]] (UMG) in 2007.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Deusner |first1=Stephen |title=Ryan Bingham & the Dead Horses: Roadhouse Sun |url=https://www.pastemagazine.com/articles/2009/06/ryan-bingham-the-dead-horses-roadhouse-sun.html|publisher=Paste Magazine |access-date=June 27, 2019 |date=June 4, 2009}}</ref>

After receiving critical acclaim for his first two studio releases on Lost Highway Records, 2007's ''[[Mescalito (album)|Mescalito]]'' and 2009's ''[[Roadhouse Sun]]'', Bingham went on to collaborate with Grammy-winning producer [[T Bone Burnett]] on the soundtrack for the acclaimed 2009 film ''[[Crazy Heart]]'', including notably cowriting and performing the film's award-winning theme song, "[[The Weary Kind]]". The title track earned Bingham an Academy Award, Golden Globe Award, and [[Critics' Choice Movie Award|Critics' Choice Award]] for "Best Song" in 2010,<ref>[http://2010.aclfestival.com/band/ryan-bingham 2010 ACL Festival: Ryan Bingham Official Bio] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110423115919/http://2010.aclfestival.com/band/ryan-bingham |date=April 23, 2011 }}</ref> as well as a Grammy Award for "Best Song Written for a Motion Picture, Television or Other Visual Media" in 2011.<ref>{{cite news |first=Gerrick |last=Kennedy |title=Grammy Awards: Ryan Bingham nabs a trophy, still puts on pants 'one leg at a time' |url=http://latimesblogs.latimes.com/music_blog/2011/02/grammy-awards-.html |work=Los Angeles Times |date=February 13, 2011 |access-date=July 5, 2011}}</ref> The [[Americana Music Association]] also honored Bingham with the organization's top [[Americana Music Honors & Awards|award]] in 2010 as "Artist of the Year".<ref>{{cite news |first=Chris |last=Talbott |title=Ryan Bingham Wins Big at Americana Awards |url=https://www.usatoday.com/life/music/news/2010-09-09-americana-awards_N.html  |work=USA Today |date=September 9, 2010 |access-date=July 5, 2011}}{{dead link|date=July 2014}}</ref>

Bingham's most recent album, ''[[American Love Song]]'', was released on February 15, 2019. A ballad from that album, "Wolves", was inspired in part by the [[March For Our Lives]] students who were dealing with grown men and women questioning their integrity on social media.<ref>{{cite magazine |last1=Newman |first1=Melinda |title=Ryan Bingham on His Haunting New Song 'Wolves' and Launching His Own Music Festival: Exclusive |url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/country/8487093/ryan-bingham-new-song-wolves-western-festival |magazine=Billboard |publisher=Billboard Magazine |access-date=June 27, 2019 |date=November 29, 2018}}</ref> The song was also featured on the TV series ''[[Yellowstone (American TV series)|Yellowstone]]''.<ref>{{cite web |title=Yellowstone – S1E7 Soundtrack A Monster Is Among Us |url=https://www.what-song.com/Tvshow/100345/Yellowstone/e/112379 |website=What-Song |access-date=June 27, 2019}}</ref> Bingham sang "Wolves" as the series' character, Walker, whom he plays on the show.<ref name="Yellowstone" />

In April 2019, Bingham partnered with [[Live Nation (events promoter)|Live Nation]] to launch his own music festival, The Western. The inaugural event took place over two days in [[Luckenbach, Texas]].<ref>{{cite web |last1=Rascoe |first1=Rachel |title=Faster Than Sound: Ryan Bingham Warms Up His Western Festival |url=https://www.austinchronicle.com/music/2019-04-19/faster-than-sound-ryan-bingham-warms-up-his-western-festival/ |website=Austin Chronicle |access-date=June 28, 2019 |date=April 19, 2019}}</ref>

== Early life ==
Bingham was born in Hobbs, New Mexico. His family relocated to the [[Midland–Odessa]] area of [[West Texas]], before eventually moving to [[Houston]]. He attended high school primarily in Houston at [[Westfield High School (Harris County, Texas)|Westfield High School]].

Bingham's mother purchased his first guitar when he was 16 years old. Although he was fascinated by music, he left his guitar dormant in his closet. Roughly a year later, Bingham hitchhiked back west to [[Laredo, Texas]], in hopes of landing a job with his father, carrying the guitar with him on the trip. Bingham's father enjoyed having neighbors over on their porch to drink beer, and one of them taught him a classical Mariachi song called "La Malaguena" in segments. Though he loved playing the song, it was the only one he would learn during his time in Laredo.

He relocated to [[Stephenville, Texas]]. There, he began learning more music while also riding on the rodeo team at [[Tarleton State University]]. It was in Stephenville that he would write arguably his most well-known hit "Southside of Heaven" in a trailer house. He also began to play local gigs there, namely a local golf course and a few small bars.

While in Stephenville, Bingham had a friend who caught wind of a job in [[Paris]], France, with the Wild West Show at the [[Disney Parks, Experiences and Products|Disney Resort]]. He bought a one-way ticket with $100 in his pocket. Upon arrival, he was informed that the manager with whom he had a mutual friend was no longer with the company, and he found himself stranded with his guitar and old rigging bag from his rodeo days. Luckily, he found some friends-of-friends within the Disney programs and began playing music in local parks for tips.

Eventually, he saved enough money to get back to Texas and moved in with a rodeo buddy near [[Fort Worth]]. His friend had a brother (Matthew "Papa" Smith) who cut hair during the day and played drums as a hobby. After an introduction and impromptu gig at an empty bar in Fort Worth, he and Papa would go on to be the founding members of Ryan Bingham and the Dead Horses.<ref name=3DotMag>{{Cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=8PLUyADYR_w|title=Ryan Bingham Interviewed by 3DotMag|publisher=[[YouTube]]}}</ref> [[Marc Ford]] of the [[Black Crowes]] was one of the few people in the bar that night. He approached Bingham after the gig with an offer to record an album.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.popmatters.com/ryan-bingham-conquers-fear-and-loathing-to-rock-the-american-dream-2495463954.html|title=Ryan Bingham Conquers Fear and Loathing to Rock the American Dream|date=December 2, 2015|website=PopMatters.com|language=en|access-date=February 23, 2019}}</ref><ref name=wellREDpodcast>{{Cite web|url=https://www.stitcher.com/s?eid=58246765|title=#100 – The 100th Episode Celebration w/ Ryan F***ing Bingham! from wellRED podcast|website=Stitcher.com}}</ref>

== Career ==
After issuing self-released "Wishbone Saloon" and "Dead Horses", the latter distributed by [[Lone Star Music]], Bingham was signed to [[Lost Highway Records]], which issued his first major label debut with ''Mescalito'' on October 2, 2007, produced by former [[Black Crowes]] guitarist [[Marc Ford]]. ''Texas Music Magazine'' has opined that Bingham "talks and sings with a whiskey-and-cigarette throat that screams hard living. Hard in a way that can make a 29-year-old sound like a 50-year-old [[Tom Waits]]."<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.binghammusic.com/ |title=Ryan Bingham's website, quoting the magazine article |website=Binghammusic.com |date=July 9, 2014 |access-date=July 27, 2014}}</ref> Bingham spent several years on the rodeo circuit. He began [[bull riding]] in his late teens.<ref>{{cite web|last=McCartney |first=Kelly |url=http://www.popmatters.com/pm/news/article/58968/no-bull-ryan-bingham-trades-in-rodeos-for-nightclubs/ |title=Pop Matters website interview with Ryan Bingham |website=Popmatters.com |access-date=July 27, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.gactv.com/gac/ar_artists_a-z/article/0,3028,GAC_26071_5781672_,00.html |title=Artists: Artists A to Z: Ryan Bingham Biography: Great American Country |website=Gactv.com |date=June 27, 2014 |access-date=July 27, 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120211171659/http://www.gactv.com/gac/ar_artists_a-z/article/0,3028,GAC_26071_5781672_,00.html |archive-date=February 11, 2012 |url-status=dead }}</ref>

Bingham's former band, The Dead Horses, was composed of Matthew "Papa" Smith ([[drums]]), Corby Schaub (guitar and [[mandolin]]) and Marc Ford's son Elijah ([[bass guitar|bass]]). The bass player on ''Mescalito'' was Jeb Venable (a.k.a. Jeb Stuart), with Joe Allen credited as well, plus a contribution from [[John Bazz]] on [[upright bass]]. Bingham appeared with the [[Drive-by Truckers]] on ''[[Austin City Limits]]'' in October 2007. The first single from ''Mescalito'', titled "Southside of Heaven", was released on November 30, 2007. The second single was entitled "Bread and Water".

On June 2, 2009, Ryan Bingham and The Dead Horses released their second studio album titled ''[[Roadhouse Sun]]'' via Lost Highway Records. It was once again produced by [[Marc Ford]].
[[File:Ryan Bingham - Roadhouse Sun Image.jpg|thumb|left|Ryan Bingham from his 2009 release – Roadhouse Sun]]

Bingham performed two songs for the soundtrack of the movie ''[[Crazy Heart]]'', including "I Don't Know" and the theme song, "[[The Weary Kind]]". The song was co-written by Bingham and producer, T Bone Burnett. Bingham also played a small role in the film. On January 17, 2010, Bingham was awarded the [[Golden Globe Award for Best Original Song|Golden Globe for Best Original Song]] for "The Weary Kind". The song also won the 2010 [[Academy Award for Best Original Song]],<ref>{{cite magazine |url=http://oscar-watch.ew.com/2010/02/02/oscar-nominations-announced/ |title=Oscar nominations announced |year=2010 |magazine=[[Entertainment Weekly|ew.com]] |access-date=February 2, 2010 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100205043942/http://oscar-watch.ew.com/2010/02/02/oscar-nominations-announced/ |archive-date=February 5, 2010 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cmt.com/news/country-music/1633370/jeff-bridges-ryan-bingham-t-bone-burnett-win-oscars-for-crazy-heart.jhtml|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100311182223/http://www.cmt.com/news/country-music/1633370/jeff-bridges-ryan-bingham-t-bone-burnett-win-oscars-for-crazy-heart.jhtml|url-status=dead|archive-date=March 11, 2010|title=Jeff Bridges, Ryan Bingham, T Bone Burnett Win Oscars for Crazy Heart|date=March 8, 2010|work=[[CMT (American TV channel)|CMT]]|access-date=March 8, 2010}}</ref> the 2010 Grammy award for [[Best Song Written for a Motion Picture, Television or Other Visual Media]],<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.grammy.com/grammys/artists/ryan-bingham|title=Ryan Bingham|date=May 22, 2018|website=Grammy.com}}</ref> as well as Song of the Year at the 9th Annual [[Americana Music Association]] awards.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sesac.com/News/News_Details.aspx?id=1362|title=ARTISTRY WINS DURING 9th ANNUAL AMERICANA MUSIC ASSOCIATION HONORS & AWARDS, Ryan also played at the ACL festival in 2011|date=September 10, 2010|website=Sesac.com|access-date=September 13, 2010}}</ref>

Bingham rejoined with his band the Dead Horses to release their third studio album, ''[[Junky Star]]'', on August 31, 2010. The album debuted in the Top 20 on the [[Billboard 200|''Billboard'' 200]] Chart<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.billboard.com/#/album/ryan-bingham-the-dead-horses/junky-star/1386221|title=Billboard – Music Charts, News, Photos & Video|website=Billboard.com}}</ref> & in the Top 10 on the Billboard Rock Album Chart,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.billboard.com/#/charts/rock-albums?chartDate=2010-09-19|title=Billboard – Music Charts, News, Photos & Video|website=Billboard.com}}</ref> making ''Junky Star'' Bingham's highest charting and most successful release to date.

In 2012, Bingham parted ways with the Dead Horses and record label Lost Highway Records to release his fourth studio album, ''[[Tomorrowland (Ryan Bingham album)|Tomorrowland]]'', on his own Axster Bingham Records label.<ref name="pastemagazine.com">{{Cite web|url=https://www.pastemagazine.com/articles/2012/09/ryan-bingham-tomorrowland.html|title=Ryan Bingham: Tomorrowland|date=September 17, 2012|website=Pastemagazine.com}}</ref> Bingham co-produced the album with musician/producer [[Justin Stanley]]. The first single released from ''Tomorrowland'' was "Heart of Rhythm". Both the single and the official lyric video debuted on Americansongwriter.com on July 30, 2012.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://americansongwriter.com/premiere-ryan-bingham-heart-of-rhythm-lyric-video/evan-schlansky/|title=Premiere: Ryan Bingham, "Heart of Rhythm" (Lyric Video) |website=Americansongwriter.com|date=July 30, 2012}}</ref> Bingham's second ''Tomorrowland'' single "Guess Who's Knockin" debuted on rollingstone.com on September 6, 2012.<ref>{{Cite magazine|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-news/song-premiere-ryan-bingham-guess-whos-knocking-237864/|title=Song Premiere: Ryan Bingham, 'Guess Who's Knocking'|magazine=[[Rolling Stone]]|date=September 6, 2012}}</ref> The official music video for "Guess Who's Knocking" premiered on pastmagazine.com October 4, 2012.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.pastemagazine.com/blogs/av/2012/10/video-premiere-ryan-bingham.html|title=Video Premiere: Ryan Bingham – "Guess Who's Knocking"|date=October 4, 2012|website=Pastemagazine.com}}</ref>

In 2013, Bingham's song "For Anyone's Sake" appeared in the closing credits of the feature film ''[[Joe (2013 film)|Joe]]'', starring [[Nicolas Cage]]. Bingham wrote the song for the film, and it was released as part of the film's original soundtrack in April 2014.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://itunes.apple.com/us/album/joe-original-motion-picture-soundtrack/847533862|title=Joe (Original Motion Picture Soundtrack) by Jeff McIlwain & David Wingo|date=April 8, 2014|website=Itunes.apple.com}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.amazon.com/gp/product/B00J7MEKD0/ref=dm_ws_sp_ps_dp|title=Joe|website=Amazon.com}}</ref> In the same year, Bingham also wrote and recorded "Until I'm One With You", the theme song for [[FX (TV channel)|FX]] TV drama series ''[[The Bridge (2013 TV series)|The Bridge]]''. The song is Bingham's first screen track since his Academy Award win for best theme song in 2010. "Until I'm One with You" was released as a digital single on Bingham's own Axster Bingham Records label on June 25, 2013.<ref name="billboard.com">Phil Gallo, [http://www.billboard.com/articles/news/1568109/ryan-bingham-pens-theme-for-fxs-bridge-first-screen-track-since-oscar-win "Ryan Bingham Pens Theme For FX's 'Bridge'; First Screen Track Since Oscar Win"], ''Billboard.com'', 06/25/13</ref>

In 2014, Bingham starred opposite [[Imogen Poots]] in the independent film ''A Country Called Home'', directed and co-written by his wife, Anna Axster. Bingham also wrote and recorded the film's title track "A Country Called Home". The song was released digitally through Bingham's own label, Axster Bingham Records, on May 6, 2016.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://itunes.apple.com/us/album/a-country-called-home-single/1104417328|title=A Country Called Home – Single by Ryan Bingham|date=May 6, 2016|website=Itunes.apple.com}}</ref>

Bingham's fifth studio album ''[[Fear and Saturday Night]]'' was recorded mostly live at Plyrz Studio outside of Los Angeles, California.<ref name="nodepression.com">{{cite web |url=http://nodepression.com/album-review/ryan-bingham-returns-fear-and-saturday-night |title=Ryan Bingham Returns with 'Fear and Saturday Night' &#124; No Depression |website=nodepression.com |access-date=January 15, 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150318220543/http://nodepression.com/album-review/ryan-bingham-returns-fear-and-saturday-night |archive-date=March 18, 2015 |url-status=dead}}</ref> The album was co-produced by Jim Scott and released through Axster Bingham Records on January 20, 2015. The album's first single "Radio" was released on December 9, 2014. In a 2016 interview with [[Rolling Stone magazine]], Bingham shared, "'Radio' is a song I wrote about the thoughts, memories, and emotions that roll through my mind. The radio that's constantly playing in your head, night and day."<ref>{{Cite magazine|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-country/watch-ryan-binghams-intense-live-radio-video-112878/|title=Watch Ryan Bingham's Intense Live 'Radio' Video|magazine=[[Rolling Stone]]|date=September 30, 2016}}</ref>

On August 6, 2016, Bingham recorded his first live album, ''Ryan Bingham Live'', at Whitewater Amphitheater in [[New Braunfels, Texas]]. The album was released on October 21, 2016. The entire Whitewater Amphitheater show was also filmed and streamed live by [[Amazon Music]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://ftw.usatoday.com/2016/10/song-premiere-ryan-bingham-crowd-favorite-sunrise-off-new-live-album|title=Song Premiere: Ryan Bingham crowd favorite 'Sunrise' off new live album|website=Ftw.usatoday.com|date=October 18, 2016}}</ref>

Bingham released a song titled "Back By the River" on ''The Musical Mojo of [[Dr. John]]: A Celebration of Mac and his Music'', in 2016.<ref>{{cite web|title=Press Play: New Music|url=http://www.tulsaworld.com/weekend/pressplay/press-play-new-music/article_2197869b-6827-5d5e-8a0b-45232cf5bc84.html|website=Tulsaworld.com|access-date=September 14, 2016}}</ref>

In 2018–2020, Bingham has a guest role in the [[Western (genre)#Contemporary Western|contemporary Western]] television show, ''[[Yellowstone (American TV series)|Yellowstone]]'', as Walker, an itinerant [[ranch hand]].<ref name="Yellowstone">{{cite web |title=Yellowstone – Season 1 – TV Series {{!}} Paramount Network |url=https://www.paramountnetwork.com/shows/yellowstone/iutiiw/season-1 |access-date=June 22, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Yellowstone – Season 2 – TV Series {{!}} Paramount Network |url=https://www.paramountnetwork.com/shows/yellowstone/e7flgl/season-2 |access-date=June 22, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Yellowstone – Season 3 – TV Series {{!}} Paramount Network |url=https://www.paramountnetwork.com/shows/yellowstone/g4h152/season-3 |access-date=September 20, 2020}}</ref>

In December 2018, Bingham announced that he would be releasing his sixth studio album ''American Love Song'' in February 2019.

In March 2020, Bingham began posting various covers and released songs on his Youtube channel in a series known as the Cantina Sessions throughout the [[COVID-19 pandemic|COVID-19 Pandemic]], he continued such until the end of 2020.

== Reception ==
Bingham has appeared as a guest on [[Bob Harris (radio)|Bob Harris]]'s Country Show on the [[BBC Radio 2|BBC's Radio 2]]. Daryl Easlea, writing for the BBC's folk and country review, said: "Bingham will be one of the names to drop in 2008, with an album that sounds as if it's been unearthed from 1972."<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/music/reviews/jg54/|archive-url=https://archive.today/20120723012944/http://www.bbc.co.uk/music/reviews/jg54|url-status=dead|title=BBC – Music – Review of Ryan Bingham – Mescalito|first=Daryl|last=Easlea|website=Bbc.co.uk|archive-date=July 23, 2012|access-date=February 17, 2020}}</ref>
[[File:Ryan Bingham Ron Baker 3.jpg|thumb|left|Ryan Bingham & Joe Ely – Antone's during SXSW 2008 – Austin, TX.]]
''[[Rolling Stone]]'' magazine gave ''Mescalito'' three out of five stars and wrote that Bingham "earns his sepia-toned album cover with a dusty wood-and-steel sound, and despite being twenty-five, sings like [[Steve Earle]]'s dad."<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/reviews/album/16496481/review/18057124/mescalito?rating=11 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090114090514/http://www.rollingstone.com/reviews/album/16496481/review/18057124/mescalito?rating=11 |url-status=dead |archive-date=January 14, 2009 |title=Mescalito : Ryan Bingham : Review |publisher=[[Rolling Stone]]|access-date=July 27, 2014}}</ref>

''[[PopMatters]]'' review of ''Tomorrowland'' awarded the album with 8 out of 10 stars. Greg M. Scwartz, writing for PopMatters wrote, that "The one-time pro rodeo rider turned Texas troubadour has blues, country, and Americana influences that are certainly still there. But at his core, Bingham has always been a rock 'n' roller and ''Tomorrowland'' features him rocking at his best."<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.popmatters.com/pm/review/164086-ryan-bingham-tomorrowland/ |title=Ryan Bingham: Tomorrowland < PopMatters |website=www.popmatters.com |access-date=January 15, 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121025002058/http://www.popmatters.com/pm/review/164086-ryan-bingham-tomorrowland/ |archive-date=October 25, 2012 |url-status=dead}}</ref>

''Tomorrowland'' was also reviewed by Nico Isaac from [[Paste (magazine)]]. Isaac wrote: "Tomorrowland is like a good, ol' fashioned rock anthem of kiss-my-asschaps autonomy... One thing's for sure Tomorrowland- the album and the red-blooded, rattlesnake-eating rebellious attitude—is no place for the weary kind."<ref name="pastemagazine.com" />
